[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:ssrf-defense/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] This article is focused on providing clear, simple, actionable guidance for providing Input Validation security functionality in your applications.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input validation is performed to ensure only properly formed data is entering the workflow in an information system, preventing malformed data from persisting in the database and triggering malfunction of various downstream components.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input validation should happen as early as possible in the data flow, preferably as soon as the data is received from the external party.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Data from all potentially untrusted sources should be subject to input validation, including not only Internet-facing web clients but also backend feeds over extranets, from suppliers, partners, vendors or regulators, each of which may be compromised on their own and start sending malformed data.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input Validation should not be used as the *primary* method of preventing XSS, SQL Injection and other attacks which are covered in respective cheat sheets but can significantly contribute to reducing their impact if implemented properly.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] It is always recommended to prevent attacks as early as possible in the processing of the user's (attacker's) request.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input validation can be used to detect unauthorized input before it is processed by the application.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] It is a common mistake to use denylist validation in order to try to detect possibly dangerous characters and patterns like the apostrophe `'` character, the string `1=1`, or the `<script>` tag, but this is a massively flawed approach as it is trivial for an attacker to bypass such filters.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Plus, such filters frequently prevent authorized input, like `O'Brian`, where the `'` character is fully legitimate.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] For more information on XSS filter evasion please see this wiki page.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] While denylisting can be useful as an additional layer of defense to catch some common malicious patterns, it should not be relied upon as the primary method.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Allowlisting remains the more robust and secure approach for preventing potentially harmful input.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Allowlist validation is appropriate for all input fields provided by the user.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Allowlist validation involves defining exactly what IS authorized, and by definition, everything else is not authorized.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If it's well structured data, like dates, social security numbers, zip codes, email addresses, etc. then the developer should be able to define a very strong validation pattern, usually based on regular expressions, for validating such input.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If the input field comes from a fixed set of options, like a drop down list or radio buttons, then the input needs to match exactly one of the values offered to the user in the first place.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Any failure to validate a value against this discrete list of options on the server side is a high security event and should be logged as a high severity event as it indicates that an attacker is tampering with the client-side code.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Free-form text, especially with Unicode characters, is perceived as difficult to validate due to a relatively large space of characters that need to be allowed.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] It's also free-form text input that highlights the importance of proper context-aware output encoding and quite clearly demonstrates that input validation is **not** the primary safeguards against Cross-Site Scripting.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If your users want to type apostrophe `'` or less-than sign `<` in their comment field, they might have perfectly legitimate reason for that and the application's job is to properly handle it throughout the whole life cycle of the data.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Developing regular expressions can be complicated, and is well beyond the scope of this cheat sheet.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] There are lots of resources on the internet about how to write regular expressions, including this site and the OWASP Validation Regex Repository.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] When designing regular expressions, be aware of RegEx Denial of Service (ReDoS) attacks.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] These attacks cause a program using a poorly designed Regular Expression to operate very slowly and utilize CPU resources for a very long time.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Example validating the parameter "zip" using a regular expression.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Some Allowlist validators have also been predefined in various open source packages that you can leverage.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input validation **must** be implemented on the server-side before any data is processed by an application’s functions, as any JavaScript-based input validation performed on the client-side can be circumvented by an attacker who disables JavaScript or uses a web proxy.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Implementing both client-side JavaScript-based validation for UX and server-side validation for security is the recommended approach, leveraging each for their respective strengths.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] It is very difficult to validate rich content submitted by a user.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] For more information, please see the XSS cheat sheet on Sanitizing HTML Markup with a Library Designed for the Job.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] All user data controlled must be encoded when returned in the HTML page to prevent the execution of malicious data (e.g.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The type of encoding is specific to the context of the page where the user controlled data is inserted.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] For example, HTML entity encoding is appropriate for data placed into the HTML body.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] However, user data placed into a script would need JavaScript specific output encoding.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Many websites allow users to upload files, such as a profile picture or more.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] This section helps provide that feature securely.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The upload feature should be using an allowlist approach to only allow specific file types and extensions.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The format of email addresses is defined by RFC 5321, and is far more complicated than most people realise.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Properly parsing email addresses for validity with regular expressions is very complicated, although there are a number of publicly available documents on regex.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The biggest caveat on this is that although the RFC defines a very flexible format for email addresses, most real world implementations (such as mail servers) use a far more restricted address format, meaning that they will reject addresses that are *technically* valid.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Although they may be technically correct, these addresses are of little use if your application will not be able to actually send emails to them.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] As such, the best way to validate email addresses is to perform some basic initial validation, and then pass the address to the mail server and catch the exception if it rejects it.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] This means that the application can be confident that its mail server can send emails to any addresses it accepts.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Semantic validation is about determining whether the email address is correct and legitimate.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The most common way to do this is to send an email to the user, and require that they click a link in the email, or enter a code that has been sent to them.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] After validating the ownership of the email address, the user should then be required to authenticate on the application through the usual mechanism.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] In some cases, users may not want to give their real email address when registering on the application, and will instead provide a disposable email address.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] These are publicly available addresses that do not require the user to authenticate, and are typically used to reduce the amount of spam received by users' primary email addresses.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Blocking disposable email addresses is almost impossible, as there are a large number of websites offering these services, with new domains being created every day.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] There are a number of publicly available lists and commercial lists of known disposable domains, but these will always be incomplete.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If these lists are used to block the use of disposable email addresses then the user should be presented with a message explaining why they are blocked (although they are likely to simply search for another disposable provider rather than giving their legitimate address).
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If it is essential that disposable email addresses are blocked, then registrations should only be allowed from specifically-allowed email providers.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] However, if this includes public providers such as Google or Yahoo, users can simply register their own disposable address with them.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Sub-addressing allows a user to specify a *tag* in the local part of the email address (before the `@` sign), which will be ignored by the mail server.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Many mail providers (such as Microsoft Exchange) do not support sub-addressing.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The most notable provider who does is Gmail, although there are many others that also do.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Some users will use a different *tag* for each website they register on, so that if they start receiving spam to one of the sub-addresses they can identify which website leaked or sold their email address.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Because it could allow users to register multiple accounts with a single email address, some sites may wish to block sub-addressing by stripping out everything between the `+` and `@` signs.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] This is not generally recommended, as it suggests that the website owner is either unaware of sub-addressing or wishes to prevent users from identifying them when they leak or sell email addresses.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Additionally, it can be trivially bypassed by using disposable email addresses, or simply registering multiple email accounts with a trusted provider.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] In computing, **data validation** or **input validation** is the process of ensuring data has undergone data cleansing to confirm it has data quality, that is, that it is both correct and useful.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] It uses routines, often called "validation rules", "validation constraints", or "check routines", that check for correctness, meaningfulness, and security of data that are input to the system.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] The rules may be implemented through the automated facilities of a data dictionary, or by the inclusion of explicit application program validation logic of the computer and its application.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This is distinct from formal verification, which attempts to prove or disprove the correctness of algorithms for implementing a specification or property.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Data validation is intended to provide certain well-defined guarantees for fitness and consistency of data in an application or automated system.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Data validation rules can be defined and designed using various methodologies, and be deployed in various contexts.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Their implementation can use declarative data integrity rules, or procedure-based business rules.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] The guarantees of data validation do not necessarily include accuracy, and it is possible for data entry errors such as misspellings to be accepted as valid.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Other clerical and/or computer controls may be applied to reduce inaccuracy within a system.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] In evaluating the basics of data validation, generalizations can be made regarding the different kinds of validation according to their scope, complexity, and purpose.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Data type validation is customarily carried out on one or more simple data fields.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] The simplest kind of data type validation verifies that the individual characters provided through user input are consistent with the expected characters of one or more known primitive data types as defined in a programming language or data storage and retrieval mechanism.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, an integer field may require input to use only characters 0 through 9.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Simple range and constraint validation may examine input for consistency with a minimum/maximum range, or consistency with a test for evaluating a sequence of characters, such as one or more tests against regular expressions.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, a counter value may be required to be a non-negative integer, and a password may be required to meet a minimum length and contain characters from multiple categories.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Code and cross-reference validation includes operations to verify that data is consistent with one or more possibly-external rules, requirements, or collections relevant to a particular organization, context or set of underlying assumptions.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] These additional validity constraints may involve cross-referencing supplied data with a known look-up table or directory information service such as LDAP.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, a user-provided country code might be required to identify a current geopolitical region.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Structured validation allows for the combination of other kinds of validation, along with more complex processing.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Such complex processing may include the testing of conditional constraints for an entire complex data object or set of process operations within a system.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Consistency validation ensures that data is logical.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, the delivery date of an order can be prohibited from preceding its shipment date.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Multiple kinds of data validation are relevant to 10-digit pre-2007 ISBNs (the 2005 edition of ISO 2108 required ISBNs to have 13 digits from 2007 onwards).
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Checks to ascertain that only expected characters are present in a field.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example a numeric field may only allow the digits 0–9, the decimal point and perhaps a minus sign or commas.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] An e-mail address might require at least one @ sign and various other structural details.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] can be effective ways to implement such checks.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Numerical fields may be added together for all records in a batch.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] The batch total is entered and the computer checks that the total is correct, e.g., add the 'Total Cost' field of a number of transactions together.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Checks that record has a valid number of related records.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, if a contact record is classified as "customer" then it must have at least one associated order (cardinality > 0).
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This type of rule can be complicated by additional conditions.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, if a contact record in a payroll database is classified as "former employee" then it must not have any associated salary payments after the separation date (cardinality = 0).
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] To support error detection, an extra digit is added to a number which is calculated from the other digits.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Checks fields to ensure data in these fields correspond, e.g., if expiration date is in the past then status is not "active".
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Compares data in different systems to ensure it is consistent.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Systems may represent the same data differently, in which case comparison requires transformation (e.g., one system may store customer name in a single Name field as 'Doe, John Q', while another uses First_Name 'John' and Last_Name 'Doe' and Middle_Name 'Quality').
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Checks input conformance with typed data.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, an input box accepting numeric data may reject the letter 'O'.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Checks that a file with a specified name exists.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This check is essential for programs that use file handling.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Checks that the data is in a specified format (template), e.g., dates have to be in the format YYYY-MM-DD.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Regular expressions may be used for this kind of validation.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Checks that data is present, e.g., customers may be required to have an email address.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Checks that the data is within a specified range of values, e.g., a probability must be between 0 and 1.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] tables can be linked through foreign key and primary key.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] If values in the foreign key field are not constrained by internal mechanisms, then they should be validated to ensure that the referencing table always refers to a row in the referenced table.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Looks for spelling and grammatical errors.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This can be applied to several fields (i.e.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] A table look up check compares data to a collection of allowed values.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Enforcement action typically rejects the data entry request and requires the input actor to make a change that brings the data into compliance.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This is most suitable for interactive use, where a real person is sitting on the computer and making entry.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] It also works well for batch upload, where a file input may be rejected and a set of messages sent back to the input source for why the data is rejected.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Another form of enforcement action involves automatically changing the data and saving a conformant version instead of the original version.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This is most suitable for cosmetic change.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, converting an [all-caps] entry to a [Pascal case] entry does not need user input.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] An inappropriate use of automatic enforcement would be in situations where the enforcement leads to loss of business information.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] For example, saving a truncated comment if the length is longer than expected.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This is not typically a good thing since it may result in loss of significant data.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Advisory actions typically allow data to be entered unchanged but sends a message to the source actor indicating those validation issues that were encountered.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This is most suitable for non-interactive system, for systems where the change is not business critical, for cleansing steps of existing data and for verification steps of an entry process.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Verification actions are special cases of advisory actions.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] In this case, the source actor is asked to verify that this data is what they would really want to enter, in the light of a suggestion to the contrary.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Here, the check step suggests an alternative (e.g., a check of a mailing address returns a different way of formatting that address or suggests a different address altogether).
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] You would want in this case, to give the user the option of accepting the recommendation or keeping their version.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] This is not a strict validation process, by design and is useful for capturing addresses to a new location or to a location that is not yet supported by the validation databases.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Even in cases where data validation did not find any issues, providing a log of validations that were conducted and their results is important.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Failures or omissions in data validation can lead to data corruption or a security vulnerability.
[src:ssrf-defense/input-validation] Data validation checks that data are fit for purpose, valid, sensible, reasonable and secure before they are processed.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] In Internet networking, a **private network** is a computer network that uses a private address space of IP addresses.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] These addresses are commonly used for local area networks (LANs) in residential, office, and enterprise environments.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Both the IPv4 and the IPv6 specifications define **private IP address** ranges.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Most Internet service providers (ISPs) allocate only a single publicly routable IPv4 address to each residential customer, but many homes have more than one computer, smartphone, or other Internet-connected device.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] In this situation, a network address translator (NAT/PAT) gateway is usually used to provide Internet connectivity to multiple hosts.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Private addresses are also commonly used in corporate networks which, for security reasons, are not connected directly to the Internet.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Often a proxy, SOCKS gateway, or similar devices are used to provide restricted Internet access to network-internal users.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Private network addresses are not allocated to any specific organization.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Anyone may use these addresses without approval from regional or local Internet registries.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Private IP address spaces were originally defined to assist in delaying IPv4 address exhaustion.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] IP packets originating from or addressed to a private IP address cannot be routed through the public Internet.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Private addresses are often seen as enhancing network security for the internal network since use of private addresses internally makes it difficult for an external host to initiate a connection to an internal system.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) has directed the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) to reserve the following IPv4 address ranges for private networks.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] In practice, it is common to subdivide these ranges into smaller subnets.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] In April 2012, IANA allocated the *100.64.0.0/10* block of IPv4 addresses specifically for use in carrier-grade NAT scenarios.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] This address block should not be used on private networks or on the public Internet.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The size of the address block was selected to be large enough to uniquely number all customer access devices for all of a single operator's points of presence in a large metropolitan area such as Tokyo.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The concept of private networks has been extended in the next generation of the Internet Protocol, IPv6, and special address blocks are reserved.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The address block *fc00::/7* is reserved by IANA for unique local addresses (ULAs).
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] They are unicast addresses, but contain a 40-bit random number in the routing prefix to prevent collisions when two private networks are interconnected.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Despite being inherently *local* in usage, the IPv6 address scope of unique local addresses is global.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The first block defined is *fd00::/8*, designed for */48* routing blocks, in which users can create multiple subnets, as needed.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] A former standard proposed the use of *site-local* addresses in the *fec0::/10* block, but because of scalability concerns and poor definition of what constitutes a *site*, its use has been deprecated since September 2004.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Another type of private networking uses the link-local address range.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The validity of link-local addresses is limited to a single link; e.g. to all computers connected to a switch, or to one wireless network.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Hosts on different sides of a network bridge are also on the same link, whereas hosts on different sides of a network router are on different links.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] In IPv4, the utility of link-local addresses is in zero-configuration networking when Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) services are not available and manual configuration by a network administrator is not desirable.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] If a host on an IEEE 802 (Ethernet) network cannot obtain a network address via DHCP, an address from *169.254.1.0* to *169.254.254.255* may be assigned pseudorandomly.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The standard prescribes that address collisions must be handled gracefully.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] In IPv6, the block *fe80::/10* is reserved for IP address autoconfiguration.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The implementation of these link-local addresses is mandatory, as various functions of the IPv6 protocol depend on them.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] A special case of private link-local addresses is the loopback interface.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] These addresses are private and link-local by definition since packets never leave the host device.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] IPv4 reserves the entire class A address block *127.0.0.0/8* for use as private loopback addresses.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] It is common for packets originating in private address spaces to be misrouted onto the Internet.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Private networks often do not properly configure DNS services for addresses used internally and attempt reverse DNS lookups for these addresses, causing extra traffic to the Internet root nameservers.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] The AS112 project attempted to mitigate this load by providing special *black hole* anycast nameservers for private address ranges which only return negative result codes (*not found*) for these queries.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Organizational edge routers are usually configured to drop ingress IP traffic for these networks, which can occur either by misconfiguration or from malicious traffic using a spoofed source address.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Less commonly, ISP edge routers drop such egress traffic from customers, which reduces the impact to the Internet of such misconfigured or malicious hosts on the customer's network.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] Since the private IPv4 address space is relatively small, many private IPv4 networks unavoidably use the same address ranges.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] This can create a problem when merging such networks, as some addresses may be duplicated for multiple devices.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] In this case, networks or hosts must be renumbered, often a time-consuming task or a network address translator must be placed between the networks to translate or masquerade one of the address ranges.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] IPv6 defines unique local addresses, providing a very large private address space from which each organization can randomly or pseudo-randomly allocate a 40-bit prefix, each of which allows 65536 organizational subnets.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] With space for about one trillion (1012) prefixes, it is unlikely that two network prefixes in use by different organizations would be the same, provided each of them was selected randomly, as specified in the standard.
[src:ssrf-defense/private-network] When two such private IPv6 networks are connected or merged, the risk of an address conflict is therefore virtually absent.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The objective of the cheat sheet is to provide advice regarding the protection against Server Side Request Forgery (SSRF) attack.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet will focus on the defensive point of view and will not explain how to perform this attack.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] This talk from the security researcher Orange Tsai as well as this document provide techniques on how to perform this kind of attack.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] SSRF is an attack vector that abuses an application to interact with the internal/external network or the machine itself.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Because these two cases are very different, this cheat sheet will describe defences against them separately.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Sometimes, an application needs to perform a request to another application, often located on another network, to perform a specific task.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Depending on the business case, user input is required for the functionality to work.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The allowlist approach is a viable option since the internal application called by the *VulnerableApplication* is clearly identified in the technical/business flow.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] It can be stated that the required calls will only be targeted between those identified and trusted applications.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Several protective measures are possible at the **Application** and **Network** layers.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] To apply the **defense in depth** principle, both layers will be hardened against such attacks.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The first level of protection that comes to mind is Input validation.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] As Orange Tsai shows in his talk, depending on the programming language used, parsers can be abused.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] One possible countermeasure is to apply the allowlist approach when input validation is used because, most of the time, the format of the information expected from the user is globally known.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] In the context of SSRF, validations can be added to ensure that the input string respects the business/technical format expected.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] A regex can be used to ensure that data received is valid from a security point of view if the input data have a simple format (*e.g.* token, zip code, etc.).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Otherwise, validation should be conducted using the libraries available from the `string` object because regex for complex formats are difficult to maintain and are highly error-prone.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] User input is assumed to be non-network related and consists of the user's personal information.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Ensure that the IP address provided belongs to one of the IP addresses of the identified and trusted applications.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] After ensuring the validity of the incoming IP address, the second layer of validation is applied.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] An allowlist is created after determining all the IP addresses (v4 and v6 to avoid bypasses) of the identified and trusted applications.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The valid IP is cross-checked with that list to ensure its communication with the internal application (string strict comparison with case sensitive).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] In the attempt of validate domain names, it is apparent to do a DNS resolution to verify the existence of the domain.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Ensure that the domain name provided belongs to one of the domain names of the identified and trusted applications (the allowlisting comes to action here).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Verify that the domain name received is part of this allowlist (string strict comparison with case sensitive).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Unfortunately here, the application is still vulnerable to the `DNS pinning` bypass mentioned in this document.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Indeed, a DNS resolution will be made when the business code will be executed.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Monitor the domains allowlist in order to detect when any of them resolves to a/an: - Local IP address (V4 + V6). - Internal IP of your organization (expected to be in private IP ranges) for the domain that are not part of your organization.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Do not accept complete URLs from the user because URL are difficult to validate and the parser can be abused depending on the technology used as showcased by the following talk of Orange Tsai.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] If network related information is really needed then only accept a valid IP address or domain name.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The objective of the Network layer security is to prevent the *VulnerableApplication* from performing calls to arbitrary applications.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Only allowed *routes* will be available for this application in order to limit its network access to only those that it should communicate with.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The Firewall component, as a specific device or using the one provided within the operating system, will be used here to define the legitimate flows.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Network segregation (see this set of implementation advice can also be leveraged and **is highly recommended in order to block illegitimate calls directly at network level itself**.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] This case happens when a user can control a URL to an **External** resource and the application makes a request to this URL (e.g. in case of WebHooks).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Allow lists cannot be used here because the list of IPs/domains is often unknown upfront and is dynamically changing.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] In this scenario, *External* refers to any IP that doesn't belong to the internal network, and should be reached by going over the public internet.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Based on the business requirements of the above mentioned applications, the allowlist approach is not a valid solution.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Despite knowing that the block-list approach is not an impenetrable wall, it is the best solution in this scenario.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] It is informing the application what it should **not** do.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Taking into consideration the same assumption in the following example for the following sections.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Like for the case n°1, it is assumed that the `IP Address` or `domain name` is required to create the request that will be sent to the *TargetApplication*.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The first validation on the input data presented in the case n°1 on the 3 types of data will be the same for this case **BUT the second validation will differ**.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Indeed, here we must use the block-list approach.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] To prevent the `DNS pinning` attack described in this document, the application will retrieve all the IP addresses behind the domain name provided (taking records *A* + *AAAA* for IPv4 + IPv6) and it will apply the same verification described in the previous point about IP addresses.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The application will receive the protocol to use for the request via a dedicated input parameter for which it will verify the value against an allowed list of protocols (`HTTP` or `HTTPS`).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The application will receive the parameter name for the token to pass to the *TargetedApplication* via a dedicated input parameter for which it will only allow the characters set `[a-z]{1,10}`.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The application will receive the token itself via a dedicated input parameter for which it will only allow the characters set `[a-zA-Z0-9]{20}`.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The application will receive and validate (from a security point of view) any business data needed to perform a valid call.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] The application will build the HTTP POST request **using only validated information** and will send it (*don't forget to disable the support for redirection in the web client used*).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] In cloud environments SSRF is often used to access and steal credentials and access tokens from metadata services (e.g.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] AWS Instance Metadata Service, Azure Instance Metadata Service, GCP metadata server).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] IMDSv2 is an additional defence-in-depth mechanism for AWS that mitigates some of the instances of SSRF.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] To leverage this protection migrate to IMDSv2 and disable old IMDSv1.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Check out AWS documentation for more details.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Semgrep is a command-line tool for offline static analysis.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Use pre-built or custom rules to enforce code and security standards in your codebase.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Explore the Semgrep rules for SSRF to effectively identify and investigate potential SSRF vulnerabilities.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet] Draw.io schema XML code for the "case 1 for network layer protection about flows that we want to prevent" schema (printscreen are used to capture PNG image inserted into this cheat sheet).
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] In an SSRF incident, the vulnerable server issues a request to a URL supplied or altered by the attacker.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] While the supplied URL can target any endpoint, common destinations include internal networks, localhost services, and cloud metadata endpoints that are otherwise inaccessible to external users.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] SSRF is not limited to the HTTP protocol.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] The severity of an SSRF attack depends on the assets that can be accessed and whether the server’s response is observable to the attacker.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] In severe cases, SSRF can compromise cloud environments, exploit internal hosts, obtain sensitive information, or use the server as a proxy to conceal other malicious activities.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] Similar to cross-site request forgery which utilizes a web client, for example, a web browser, within the domain as a proxy for attacks; an SSRF attack utilizes a vulnerable server within the domain as a proxy.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] In this type of attack the response is displayed to the attacker.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] The server fetches the URL requested by the attacker and sends the response back to the attacker.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] In this type of attack the response is not sent back to the attacker.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] Therefore, the attacker has to devise ways to confirm this vulnerability.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] SSRF occurs when an API endpoint accesses a URL supplied by the client without verifying that the request is directed to an intended destination.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] Prevention measures include input validation, which can be supported through Static Analysis Security Testing (SAST) tooling.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] When feasible, restricting server requests to an allowlist of trusted applications is recommended, although additional safeguards may still be necessary to address hostname resolution, redirects and DNS rebindings.
[src:ssrf-defense/server-side-request-forgery] When servers must send requests to arbitrary external domains or IP addresses, network segregation is recommended to block unauthorized traffic at the network layer.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] A **whitelist** or **allowlist** is a list or register of entities that are being provided a particular privilege, service, mobility, access or recognition.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Entities on the list will be accepted, approved and/or recognized.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Whitelisting is the reverse of blacklisting, the practice of identifying entities that are denied, unrecognized, or ostracized.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Spam filters often include the ability to "whitelist" certain sender IP addresses, email addresses or domain names to protect their email from being rejected or sent to a junk mail folder.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] These can be manually maintained by the user or system administrator - but can also refer to externally maintained whitelist services.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Non-commercial whitelists are operated by various non-profit organizations, ISPs, and others interested in blocking spam.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Rather than paying fees, the sender must pass a series of tests; for example, their email server must not be an open relay and have a static IP address.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] The operator of the whitelist may remove a server from the list if complaints are received.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Commercial whitelists are a system by which an Internet service provider allows someone to bypass spam filters when sending email messages to its subscribers, in return for a pre-paid fee, either an annual or a per-message fee.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] A sender can then be more confident that their messages have reached recipients without being blocked, or having links or images stripped out of them, by spam filters.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] The purpose of commercial whitelists is to allow companies to reliably reach their customers by email.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Many websites rely on ads as a source of revenue, but the use of ad blockers is increasingly common.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Websites that detect an adblocker in use often ask for it to be disabled - or their site to be "added to the whitelist" - a standard feature of most adblockers.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] A use for whitelists is in local area network (LAN) security.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Many network admins set up MAC address whitelists, or a MAC address filter, to control who is allowed on their networks.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] This is used when encryption is not a practical solution or in tandem with encryption.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] However, it's sometimes ineffective because a MAC address can be faked.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Firewalls can usually be configured to only allow data-traffic from/to certain (ranges of) IP-addresses.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] One approach in combating viruses and malware is to whitelist software which is considered safe to run, blocking all others.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] This is particularly attractive in a corporate environment, where there are typically already restrictions on what software is approved.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Leading providers of application whitelisting technology include Bit9, Velox, McAfee, Lumension, ThreatLocker, Airlock Digital and SMAC.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] On Microsoft Windows, recent versions include AppLocker, which allows administrators to control which executable files are denied or allowed to execute.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] With AppLocker, administrators are able to create rules based on file names, publishers or file location that will allow certain files to execute.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Rules can apply to individuals or groups.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Policies are used to group users into different enforcement levels.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] For example, some users can be added to a report-only policy that will allow administrators to understand the impact before moving that user to a higher enforcement level.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Linux systems typically have AppArmor and SE Linux features available which can be used to effectively block all applications which are not explicitly whitelisted, and commercial products are also available.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] On HP-UX introduced a feature called "HP-UX Whitelisting" on 11iv3 version.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] In 2018, a journal commentary on a report on predatory publishing was released making claims that "white" and "black" are racially charged terms that need to be avoided in instances such as "whitelist" and "blacklist".
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] The premise of the journal is that "black" and "white" have negative and positive connotations respectively.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] It states that since "blacklisting" was first referred to during "the time of mass enslavement and forced deportation of Africans to work in European-held colonies in the Americas," the word is therefore related to race.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] There is no mention of "whitelist" and its origin or relation to race.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] This issue is most widely disputed in computing industries where "whitelist" and "blacklist" are prevalent (e.g.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Despite the commentary nature of the journal, some companies and individuals in others have taken to replacing "whitelist" and "blacklist" with new alternatives such as "allow list" and "deny list".
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Those adopting this change consider using the "whitelist"/"blacklist" names as a code smell.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Those that oppose these changes question its attribution to race, citing the same etymology quote that the 2018 journal uses.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] According to the remark, the term "blacklist" evolved from the term "black book" about a century ago.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] Others also note the prevalence of positive and negative connotations to "white" and "black" in the Bible, predating attributions to skin tone and slavery.
[src:ssrf-defense/whitelisting] It wasn't until the 1960s Black Power movement that "Black" became a widespread word to refer to one's race as a person of color in America (alternate to African-American) lending itself to the argument that the negative connotation behind "black" and "blacklist" both predate attribution to race.
